did.abstract: Collection consists of the records of the LGBT Community Resources Center and its predecessors the Gay People's Union (GPU), and the Gay and Lesbian Alliance at Stanford (GLAS). Included are correspondence, memoranda, office files, reference files on service organizations in Santa Clara and San Mateo Counties, log books, notebooks, questionnaires, tape recordings, videos, photographs, posters, and ephemera pertaining to the gay, lesbian, and transgender community at Stanford and the surrounding communities.

arrangement.head: Arrangement note
arrangement.p: The materials are arranged by accession.

separatedmaterial.p: Issues of Vector magazine were removed and individually cataloged as part of the Stanford University Libraries Special Collections' rare books and manuscripts collections, call number HQ75 .V43.

Consent is given on behalf of Special Collections as the owner of the physical items and is not intended to include or imply permission from the copyright owner. Such permission must be obtained from the copyright owner, heir(s) or assigns. See: http://library.stanford.edu/depts/spc/pubserv/permissions.html.
Restrictions also apply to digital representations of the original materials. Use of digital files is restricted to research and educational purposes.

accessrestrict.head: Information about Access
accessrestrict.p: Three boxes in the GPU/GLAS Records series are restricted in accordance with donor agreement. The files will remain closed until January 1, 2060 (75 years after last date of creation). Otherwise the collection is open for research; materials must be requested at least 48 hours in advance of intended use.

prefercite.head: Cite As
prefercite.p: Stanford University, LGBT Community Resources Center, Records (SC0252). Department of Special Collections and University Archives, Stanford University Libraries, Stanford, Calif.

scopecontent.head: Description of the Collection
scopecontent.p: Collection consists of the records of the LGBT Community Resources Center and its predecessors GLAS (Gay and Lesbian Alliance at Stanford) and the Gay People's Union. Included are correspondence, memoranda, office files, reference files on service organizations in Santa Clara and San Mateo Counties, log books, notebooks, VECTOR magazine, questionnaires, tape recordings, videos, photographs, posters, and ephemera pertaining to the gay, lesbian, and transgender community at Stanford and the surrounding communities. Collection also includes the records of the Gay Community of Concern, 1974-1976, a local community group; records from the Women's Collective, 1974-85; and some materials concerning the Palo Alto School Board anti-discrimination policy, 1975. Tape recordings include "Gay Life Styles," 1975, and Leonard Matlovich speaking at Stanford, 1975.

bioghist.head: Biographical / Historical
bioghist.p: In 1971, a group of students, staff, and alumni came together to form the Gay People's Union at Stanford â€“ one of the first LGBT campus organizations in America.
In 1984, Stanford Pride was established on an alumni group.

Queer Student Resources, formerly, LGBT Community Resources Center, is a student organization whose services include mentoring, diversity awareness, lecture series, support groups, workshops, and culture events. Programs represented in the records include the Gay and Lesbian Awareness Week, BGLAD (Bisexual, Gay, and Lesbian Awareness Days), AIDS Education Project, and Queer Awareness Days (QuAD).

bioghist.head: Biographical/Historical note
bioghist.p: In 1972, gay and lesbian students on the Stanford campus organized the Gay Person's Union (GPU) as a forum for open discussion of homosexuality, as a locus of political activity to promote Gay and Lesbian rights both at Stanford and the community at large, and as a safe environment for gay men and lesbians to socialize with one another. Around 1983, GPU changed its name to the Gay and Lesbian Alliance at Stanford (GLAS) to emphasize that GPU was not intended as a males-only environment and that the involvement of women as members of the organization was vital.

Over the years, GLAS became an umbrella organization under which numerous other gay and lesbian organizations on the Stanford campus operated. Most notable among these organizations within GLAS are the Women's Collective; the Gay and Lesbian Awareness (GALA) week committee, which organizes an annual GALA week activities that promote awareness and visibility of gay and lesbian students on the Stanford campus; and the Gay and Lesbian Speakers Bureau, which as part of the Residential Education policy of the University provided educational outreach to the dormitories and other residences by sending gay and lesbian students to speak about their personal experiences growing up, living at Stanford, etc.

During the early 1970s, the Gay Community of Concern (GCC) also operated on the Stanford campus. While it was a "separate entity" from GPU, many of the members of GCC were also members of GPU. In exchange for the use of GPU office space, paid GCC staffers ran the GPU office on a quid pro quo basis. When the GCC disbanded in the Winter of 1977 due to the cessation of state and federal (CETA) grant monies, its records remained in the GPU offices.

accessrestrict.head: Access to Collection
accessrestrict.p: Some materials are restricted in accordance with donor agreement and will not be opened for use until 2060.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Records reflect the foundng of the Gay People's Union (GPU) in the early 1970s, which was the original name of the Gay and Lesbian Alliance at Stanford (GLAS). Materials include office files of the GPU and GLAS from 1972-1985. Included within the general office records are the files on the various events and activities produced by GLAS as well as the records of some the organizations and committees that fell beneath the umbrella provided by GPU/GLAS. GPU materials include: log books, meeting notes, budgets, newsletters, correspondence, flyers, and items relating to Gay and Lesbian Awareness Week (GLAW). GLAS materials include: correspondence, budgets, speaker information, activism, events, scholarships, information about other gay organizations.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series is comprised of the office records of the Gay Community of Concern (GCC). Files include extensive information on gay and lesbian organizations in Santa Clara and San Mateo Counties during the early to mid-1970s. Other materials found in this series include: organizational resources (health, churches, governmental); Whitman-Radclyffe Foundation records; and the correspondence of Dick Lewis (Director of GCC). In addition, the emergency information referral records of the GCC are also held in this series, as are the counseling and referral records of individual clients.

accessrestrict.p: Counseling records are restricted and will not be opened for use until 2060.
